## USER RESEARCH

### Top 5 Pain Points (from TikTok comments, Quora, beauty editorial community signals)

1. **"I got a nude and it just looks boring / plain, not expensive"** — The most common frustration. Readers don't understand that the finish (glossy vs flat) and the undertone match matter as much as the shade. A matte nude looks cheap; a glossy one with the right undertone reads old money.

2. **"I can't figure out which shade is right for my skin tone"** — Competitors ignore this entirely. The "your nails but better" concept is what users actually want — a shade that blends so seamlessly it looks like your nails are just naturally perfect. This is undertone-dependent and nobody is telling them how.

3. **"I want something beyond sheer pink but don't know what's allowed in old money"** — Users are aware of the core shades but curious about the non-obvious ones — navy, espresso, tortoiseshell, mocha. They fear going "too far."

4. **"My nude nail color looks like dried glue / bad concealer"** — Direct from ThePinkIssue's comment observation. The polish selection was wrong for their undertone. Users need specific selection guidance, not just brand names.

5. **"Is this still a trend or am I late?"** — Aesthetic-identity readers fear being behind. They need to see old money positioned as timeless heritage (not trend-chasing) AND get a current 2026 palette update so they feel informed and ahead.

### User Sentiment

Aspirational but slightly anxious — they want to look expensive without looking like they're trying, and they need someone to tell them exactly how to select the right shade without guessing or wasting money on the wrong bottle.

